## The problem with their old site

Vistal is a business services company that had an outdated website. It looked like it was built 5 years ago, and when they showed up to pitch new clients, the website was actually working against them. They needed a full redesign: services section, team page, testimonials, contact form, everything.

## What I built for them

I designed the whole site with a clean, modern layout and a lot of whitespace. For a business like Vistal, the website needs to feel professional and trustworthy. That means no flashy effects, no neon colors. Just solid typography, clear structure, and content that's easy to scan.

Everything is built as modular components, so when Vistal wants to add a new team member or update a testimonial, it's a quick change without touching the rest of the site.

I wrote all the CSS from scratch using a fluid scaling system. No Tailwind, no Bootstrap. The site scales smoothly from a 1440px desktop down to a 320px phone screen without any weird jumps or layout breaks. It just works at every size.

The scroll animations use GSAP for fade-up effects as you move down the page. Nothing over the top, just enough movement to keep things from feeling static.

I also did full SEO setup from the start: proper meta tags on every page, Open Graph tags for social sharing, JSON-LD structured data so Google understands what the site is about, and an auto-generated sitemap. A good-looking website that nobody can find on Google is a waste of money.

## The impact

Vistal now has a website that actually helps them close deals. They've mentioned that client pitches go smoother when the prospect has already visited the site. It loads fast, it looks sharp on any device, and it shows up in search results. That's what a modern business website should do.
